export const batch157 = {
  'my-inventions.json': {
    base: { id: 'my-inventions', title: 'My Inventions', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781680230673 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Tesla reshaped modern electricity with ideas no one else could match',
        text: "Few people shaped electricity and magnetism in the late 1800s and early 1900s the way Nikola Tesla did. Alternating current, the polyphase power grid, and the AC motor all rest on his patents and theories. You cannot tell the story of the Second Industrial Revolution without naming him.\n\nTesla invented for the joy of solving problems. Fame and money never motivated him. He disliked physical labor but loved stretching his mind to the limit.\n\nMost people are more imaginative as children than as grownups.\n\nTesla admitted he stopped feeding his childhood instincts as he aged. He believed he could have changed the world even more if he had not bent to the routines of adult life that smother imagination.\n\nHe also compared himself to his brother, who died young in a horse accident. Tesla felt his own success looked small next to his brother's promise. Yet whenever young Nikola did something remarkable, his parents imagined how different life would have been if his brother had lived. The fact that his talent stirred sad memories chipped away at his confidence.\n\nAnother obstacle was the fight with his father about his future. His father wanted him to become a church clerk. Nikola wanted engineering.\n\nTesla traced his inventive streak to his mother and his powerful memory to his father, who drilled him in long recitations, mental math, and catching mistakes in written work.\n\nIn this summary, you will learn how Tesla thought, the family and environmental factors that pushed him toward invention, and lessons that can stir your own creativity.\n\nThe United States Supreme Court did not officially credit him as the inventor of the radio until 1943."
      },
      {
        title: 'Genetics and upbringing shaped Tesla into the inventor he became',
        text: "Even as a small boy, Tesla stood out. People who watched him closely could see he had a quick mind. His father, Milutin Tesla, had military training but worked as a priest in an Orthodox church. His mother, Duka Mandiç, was famous for building clever household tools and gadgets. Nikola Tesla was born on July 10, 1856, in what is now Croatia. He was the fourth of five children. His older brother Dane died in a horse accident when Nikola was five. Dane had been a child prodigy, and losing him broke the whole family. Nikola began holding back his own gifts, because every time he shone, it reminded his parents of Dane.\n\nHis father trained his memory through long passages and tough math drills. His mother came from a long line of inventors. Together, they built Nikola into the mind he later became.\n\nEach of us carries a mix of inherited traits and childhood surroundings.\n\nEven with these gifts, Tesla did not unlock his full power until much later. Beyond his brother's death, he suffered painful flashes of vivid images. Spoken words lit up as pictures in his head, and he could not always tell real sights from imagined ones.\n\nTesla believed those images came from his brain reacting strongly to the retina when it was excited.\n\nTo handle these visions, Tesla trained himself to redirect his attention. Each time one image stuck in his mind, he would build a new mental picture on top of it, so the original would not bother him.\n\nThis habit lasted until he was seventeen, when his visions started turning into inventions. So instead of the trial-and-error method used by most scientists, Tesla built and tested machines inside his head before he ever touched a tool."
      },
      {
        title: 'Tesla designed inventions in his mind before touching a single part',
        text: "Tesla's imagination set him apart from his peers. He did not need to walk to his workshop to test a new idea. He could run the whole design in his head and spot weak points before he built anything. By the time he moved from mental design to a real prototype, the result usually matched what he had pictured. He saw trial-and-error as a waste of time, energy, and money.\n\nHis visualization also sharpened his sense of observation. He could track a flash of thought back to the moment it began. This helped him link cause and effect.\n\nEvery thought usually follows some outside trigger. If you want to change what you think, change what surrounds you.\n\nTesla imagined that one day machines would perform tasks on their own with perfect accuracy. That early idea may have been the first sketch of robotics and artificial intelligence.\n\nAt age twelve, Tesla learned to push a chosen image out of his mind on command. He could not, however, control sudden flashes of light. In 1883, he visited a French manufacturer in Paris. He was invited on a shooting trip. The moment he reached the city, blinding flashes hit him. They did not fade for more than three weeks after he left.\n\nEventually, Tesla found the pattern. As he drifted toward sleep, faces and objects flickered behind his closed eyelids. If he could not see them, he could not fall asleep.\n\nAs a child, Tesla reacted strongly to women's earrings and pearls. He was also drawn to objects with sharp edges and flat surfaces."
      },
      {
        title: 'Training the body and mind opens the door to great achievement',
        text: "As a boy, Tesla was delicate. He was deeply superstitious and struggled to manage his fears. Books became a refuge. One book that helped him steady his feelings was Abafi, written by the famous Hungarian author Josika.\n\nHe taught himself to give up vices like gambling, smoking, and heavy coffee drinking. Slowly, his willpower caught up with his passions.\n\nStrong character is essential to greatness and to solving real problems.\n\nWe live in an age of distraction. The endless flood of information shortens attention and puts lives at risk in both small and large ways. Tesla had to learn the value of quiet focus from an early age. To keep our minds and bodies working well, we must watch what we put into them. Too much tea, coffee, tobacco, or alcohol hurts the brain. Tesla held the same weight for thirty-five years because he had trained his appetite.\n\nSharp observation and resourcefulness are vital traits for any inventor.\n\nTesla called this an inventor's instinct. Twice, that instinct saved his life. Once he was trapped underwater, hitting his head on a board each time he tried to surface. As his strength failed, he figured out he could breathe in the narrow gap between the board and the water's surface. Another time, a dam's current tried to sweep him away. He pressed his hands against the wall of the dam. When his grip began to slip, a hydraulic principle flashed in his mind: pressure depends on the surface area exposed. He turned on his side to reduce the push and escaped.\n\nRestraint of the mind and body is the foundation of every great accomplishment."
      },
      {
        title: 'A true inventor aims to save lives or ease daily living',
        text: "Tesla's earliest invention was a fishing hook and a method for catching fish, although at first he only used it to catch frogs. He built pop guns and carved wooden swords before he turned six. Soon his family moved to the nearby city of Gospic. There, Tesla attended the Normal School in preparation for the Real Gymnasium. At school, he was fascinated by water turbines, and he built and ran many models.\n\nAn inventor takes raw forces from nature and bends them to human needs.\n\nHe entered the Real Gymnasium at age ten. He excelled at math and loved physics experiments. Freehand drawing was a subject he disliked, and it nearly derailed his studies because the course was required. By his second year, he had achieved a small mechanical flight by harnessing the power of a vacuum.\n\nTesla grew seriously ill near the end of his time at the Real Gymnasium. The illness was so bad that doctors could do little. He recovered and credited Mark Twain's books, which he read during his long sickbed days.\n\nHe resumed his studies at the higher Real Gymnasium in Carlstadt, Croatia, where he spent three years living with his aunt. It was there that his physics teacher sparked his lifelong interest in electricity.\n\nWhen he finished, his parents wanted him to enter the clergy. He refused and would not go home. He fell ill again, close to death. When his father visited, Tesla made him promise to let him study engineering. His father agreed. After taking a bitter drink made from a strange bean, Tesla recovered. His father insisted he spend the next year outdoors to rebuild his strength. During that year, Tesla had many ideas but not the training to carry them out.\n\nTesla's father kept his word and sent him to the Polytechnic School in Gratz, Styria. Grateful for the chance, Tesla threw himself into his studies. He worked from three a.m. until eleven p.m. and finished near the top of every class."
      },
      {
        title: 'Tesla proved his professor wrong by inventing a rotating magnetic field',
        text: "Tesla's brilliance in class earned the respect of his professors. Two in particular shaped his early path: Professor Poeschl, who chaired theoretical and experimental physics, and Dr. Alle, his calculus instructor. When Tesla told them about his idea for a rotating magnetic field, Professor Poeschl insisted such a device was physically impossible.\n\nSometimes we sense things that defy logic. Tesla believed in chasing those instincts rather than letting bias or the limits of current knowledge hold us back. The prize is the chance to discover something extraordinary.\n\nAt first, his professor's certainty discouraged him, but his gift for mental imaging pushed him to keep going. In 1880, Tesla enrolled at the University of Prague in Bohemia to continue his studies. That move helped him make real progress toward the rotating magnetic field.\n\nAlways trust your own instincts more than authority figures, because you never know what they may lead you to find or invent.\n\nTesla fell ill again, but this time something unusual happened. His sight and hearing grew sharper than ever before. He could see farther than anyone nearby and hear sounds no one else could catch. A fly landing on a table sounded like a soft thud. He heard thunder from more than five hundred miles away, and he had to place rubber pads under his bed to get any sleep. His pulse climbed as high as 260 beats. He felt the smallest vibrations through the floor. He became thirteen times more sensitive than the average person.\n\nThat hypersensitivity gave him the missing piece. In a flash, the full image of the motor appeared in his mind. He nearly paid for the discovery with his life.\n\nThis heightened state became his new normal. Ideas flooded his mind faster than he could write them down.\n\nTesla's habit of finishing whatever he started led him to read nearly one hundred large volumes of Voltaire's works."
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing reflections on a mind far ahead of its time',
        text: "Nikola Tesla was an enigma who lived centuries ahead of his era in both his ideas and his mental strength. When he came to America, he met Thomas Edison and the two formed a close bond. In 1887, he started the Tesla Electric Company, which became the home where the motors he had visualized became real machines.\n\nWhen he hit obstacles with the motors, his mind went to work, leading to the Tesla Coil and Transformer.\n\nOne great struggle came when his turbine design threatened existing heat engines. Those who had made billions from those engines fought hard against his more efficient system. Tesla cared about solving human problems, not padding the wallets of industrial barons.\n\nHe dreamed up a plan to send electricity without wires. He believed the energy found in nature could be tapped and sent through the right device. The magnifying transmitter was built for that goal. In what he called the World System, Tesla designed a way to transmit electrical energy wirelessly and cheaply. Sadly, the world was not ready, so the system never took hold.\n\nThe World System combined his key inventions: the Tesla Transformer, the Magnifying Transmitter, the Tesla Wireless System, the Art of Individualization, and the Terrestrial Stationary Waves. If the World System had been activated, it could have linked telegraph exchanges across the planet, provided secure lines for government telegrams, spread news instantly, sent private messages, distributed music easily, guided ships without a compass, and much more.\n\nLooking back, it is clear Tesla's ideas were far ahead of their time.\n\nTesla once wrote that anyone who wants to find the secrets of the universe should think in terms of energy, frequency, and vibration.\n\nTry this\n\nTesla believed in the power of quiet reflection as a way to keep body and mind healthy.\n\nTake a few minutes each day to block out the noise around you and listen to what is happening inside.\n\nWrite down ideas the moment they arrive.\n\nYou never know where your instincts may lead you.\n\nRead it till the end?"
      }
    ]
  },

  'my-own-words.json': {
    base: { id: 'my-own-words', title: 'My Own Words', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781680325426 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'A society grows when people are willing to hold hard conversations',
        text: "Every day we have to communicate, whether at work, at school, or at home. People hold different beliefs, so clashes are common. Still, those clashes can reveal truths behind big issues and clear up misunderstandings. Professor Ruth Bader Ginsburg became a successful lawyer, but her path was long, winding, and full of barriers. In her early years, women faced many obstacles in the legal field. For a long time, women were passed over in law. As an example, only one woman had served on a federal appellate court between 1956 and the time she was writing.\n\nThe United States Constitution has recognized equal citizenship for women and men since 1972.\n\nRace is another central topic in legal debate. Many revolutions around the world have grown out of racial prejudice. This summary explores issues of race and diversity and how they shape our world. It also traces the law, its evolution, and where it stands today.\n\nMany people still hold traditional gender roles and feel confused when women step into professional roles. Important shifts have happened across every profession, but much work remains. Women's pay still trails men's, even when education and experience match. Workplaces also need better ways to support women during pregnancy and early parenting.\n\nThrough Ruth Bader Ginsburg's insights, this summary looks at the changing place of women in the legal system, the debate over the death penalty, racial discrimination, and the path toward ending bigotry. It also covers ideas like affirmative action and how they work to repair centuries of unfairness."
      },
      {
        title: 'Why the death penalty remains so controversial',
        text: "Surrounded by strong feelings on both sides, the death penalty sits at the center of legal debate. More than 140 countries have abolished it altogether. Meanwhile, 22 countries still carry out executions, with China leading in numbers and the United States among the top five.\n\nThe most common reasons for the death penalty are murder and drug trafficking, but some governments also use it against political activists and even people accused of witchcraft. What are the main arguments for keeping it? Supporters often point to the natural fear of death. If people fear execution, the logic goes, they may avoid crimes that lead to it. Some also see the death penalty as fair payback for the worst crimes.\n\nOn June 29, 2015, the Supreme Court ruled that lethal injection was an acceptable method of execution.\n\nThe United States paused capital punishment for four years before resuming it in 1976. During the 2015 vote, Ginsburg sided with Justice Breyer, who questioned whether the death penalty was constitutional. He laid out four arguments against it.\n\nFirst, accuracy or reliability. The court system is run by people, and people can be corrupt or simply wrong. Since 1976, more than one hundred people sentenced to death were later found innocent. For some, that discovery came years after they had been executed.\n\nSecond, arbitrariness. Race and geography unfairly shape who gets sentenced to death.\n\nThird, time. Executions often happen up to twenty years after the sentence. Many appeals explain the long wait, and some of those years are spent in harsh conditions like solitary confinement.\n\nFourth, declining use. In 2014, forty-three US states did not carry out a single execution."
      },
      {
        title: 'Gender bias has weakened but not disappeared',
        text: "More women are entering the legal field, but bias still lingers. Where did this prejudice come from, and what can be done to stop it?\n\nMen in the law long treated women as unfit to be lawyers, let alone judges. This unbending belief kept women out of legal debate for many years. Yet even ancient myths pushed back against that view. In Greek mythology, the goddess of justice was Pallas Athena, who set up a court to break the cycle of revenge.\n\nFor centuries, the dismissal of women as active legal voices only grew. The shift began in 1869, when Arabella Mansfield became the first woman admitted to the bar. At the same time, St. Louis Law School became the first to open its doors to women. Even after that, the struggles continued. Women faced prejudice in law school and on the job. The textbooks of that era reflected the bias. A property casebook from 1968 compared land to women and claimed both were made to be owned.\n\nHow far have we come? Since the 1960s, the share of women practicing law has risen from three percent to around thirty percent. Despite many obstacles, women refused to be silenced. Still, the long shadow of discrimination shaped the field. Today, women get more recognition, but a striking gap remains between how men and women are seen. Women are less likely to speak up in class because they keep doubting their own ability. When men struggle with a subject, they blame the difficulty. When women struggle, they blame themselves. Centuries of being told they do not belong leave deep marks.\n\nIf you have been told over and over that you do not belong, it is hard not to doubt yourself."
      },
      {
        title: 'Building real equality in the workplace',
        text: "Women still face barriers in law school and in the profession, and social science can help us see why. Employers often rely on a common stereotype that women will only work for a short time before having children and leaving. A study from Yale University reported that around sixty percent of women become less active at work after having kids.\n\nBut that picture does not match reality. Harvard's Dean Elena Kagan countered the Yale research with a study showing a different pattern. About ninety-three percent of women who stepped away from work for any reason wanted to return to practice afterward. The point is that these choices belong to women themselves, not to assumptions about them. Feminism gave women the freedom to choose their own paths.\n\nLiberty opens the door to happiness and lets us be our true selves. With liberty, we can speak our minds and hold open discussions. For too long, silenced voices can finally be heard. Of course, some speech causes real harm, which is why laws exist. Open discussion matters, but the goal is to stay as fair and objective as possible. Without free speech, ordinary conversation gives us strong protection against lies and harmful ideas.\n\nFree speech is a powerful tool, but it should not be used to spread hate.\n\nThe first step to power is making yourself heard and visible. After that, you prove your competence. The more women in the legal field, the weaker the old obstacles become. Trailblazing female lawyers break unfair rules and inspire others. It is much easier to dream big when you can see someone like you already leading the way. Influential women in every line of work push young girls around the world to aim high."
      },
      {
        title: 'Racial discrimination and its lasting damage',
        text: "Racial discrimination is just as devastating as gender bias. Different forms of bias cannot be ranked, but racial and gender prejudice share the same roots. Both were promoted by white men and grew into systems that left deep, lasting damage. Discrimination is not only about Black people in the legal system. The numbers are grim. Black people are arrested far more often than white people. Once convicted, they tend to receive longer sentences. In 2001, statistics showed that one in three Black boys would be arrested at some point in his life. That pattern does not mean Black people commit more crimes. It shows that police see them as suspects more often. Hispanic people face similar unfairness. They are about 3.1 times more likely to be jailed than their white neighbors.\n\nThese outcomes do not come from open racial hatred alone. Systemic bias shapes them. In the United States, the legal system often runs on two sets of rules: one for the white and wealthy, and another for the poor and people of color.\n\nJustice grows richer when its judges bring different backgrounds and experiences. It grows poorer when nearly everyone comes from the same mold.\n\nThere is no benefit in any form of segregation, especially when it is based on race. Every race, class, and gender can contribute as much as any other. So we should never accept inequality. Change will not happen on its own. Every authority, including those in law, must face the inequality it built and the harm it still causes. Racial bias shows up in almost every setting, and we have to keep talking about it. No race is superior. Everyone can live side by side in peace if we try.\n\nStopping racial segregation requires every workplace, school, and social space to recognize the value of diversity.\n\nAs of 2022, three of the nine justices on the US Supreme Court are women. One-third of federal judges are also women."
      },
      {
        title: 'Fighting discrimination and encouraging diversity',
        text: "Several tools have been built to repair the damage of centuries of bias in the workplace. One is affirmative action, which makes sure qualified people from designated groups get fair chances at jobs. These programs help skilled professionals appear at every level of a company's workforce and can open the door to a more diverse staff.\n\nAffirmative action does more than lift individuals. It lifts entire communities by creating a richer, more dynamic social mix. These measures address the long legacy of unfairness and help build a society where everyone has a real chance.\n\nAffirmative action also brings economic benefits. A more diverse team is often more creative and better at solving hard problems. A more educated workforce drives economic growth.\n\nAffirmative action, sometimes called positive discrimination, is a set of policies that brings minority groups into areas where they have been underrepresented.\n\nSome people argue affirmative action is unfair because it limits chances for people who played no part in past discrimination. But the harm caused by centuries of bias is so deep that everyone should share in fixing it.\n\nFor example, healthcare insurance should reach the weak or sick members of society, even alongside affirmative action. Sooner or later, all of us grow old. Health insurance is one of the best protections a person can have. Accessible health coverage means everyone can get care, regardless of their bank account, which leads to better health and a stronger society.\n\nEvery member of the community matters. There is no real diversity if we only pay attention to one group.\n\nWe all gain from a more diverse and inclusive society that understands, accommodates, and even celebrates our differences while pulling together for the common good."
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thoughts on building a fairer world',
        text: "The world is changing, and people need to understand how those changes touch their lives. Hard conversations about feminism, racial segregation, and criminal punishment are necessary if we want to grow. If we do not end every form of segregation, whether by gender, race, or class, those divisions can become weapons that tear the world apart. We must not let that happen. Every person shares the responsibility of building peace in their community. If we teach ourselves and the people around us to live with one another in love, life will be far better.\n\nLet us set aside every bias based on gender. An average woman should have the same privileges as an average man. A woman should be free to pursue any career she wants, all the way to the top. With more female leaders, women have already shown that they deserve respect and equal treatment. Schools, organizations, and society as a whole must rise to that call and create real space for women to thrive. Hopefully, a day will come when this fight for justice ends in victory. Every woman and every person of color will be treated for their worth as a person, not pushed to the side and denied life-changing chances. To make that happen, each of us has to play a part in building a world without discrimination.\n\nTry this\n\nMake a list of new skills you want to learn and research the steps to pick them up. Speak out against discrimination or unfairness at home or at work. Everyone benefits when society focuses on building everyone's capacity equally.\n\nRead it till the end?"
      }
    ]
  },

  'naked-economics.json': {
    base: { id: 'naked-economics', title: 'Naked Economics', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781680457902 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Trade can speed a country forward faster than almost anything else',
        text: "If governments alone could guarantee a strong economy, countries with heavy state control like North Korea, Oman, and Cuba would top the world. They do not. Governments do some things well and many things badly. A state can regulate an economy into the ground.\n\nBig national change begins with small steps taken by ordinary citizens.\n\nThat is why private enterprise matters. At the same time, we have to watch out for monopolies. Monopolies kill the drive to innovate or serve customers well. The danger of monopoly is the main reason neither the government nor any single private group should hold all the power. The government should not be the sole provider of a product or service unless there is strong proof that private firms would fail at it.\n\nConsider driving licenses. To drive legally, you need one. In most countries, motor licensing offices belong to the government. Because customers have no choice, the workers there can be rude without fear of losing business. No matter how harsh a clerk is, you still have to come back when your license expires. Workers at private firms usually treat customers better because they need their business, although they may issue licenses to people who should not get them. The best answer is a partnership between government and private enterprise.\n\nA market economy is to economics what democracy is to government. It is a decent, if flawed, choice among many bad ones.\n\nThe government works like a surgeon's tool. In the right hands, it can support healthy growth. In the wrong hands, it can cause real harm."
      },
      {
        title: 'Why you do not live like Bill Gates',
        text: "Unlike ancient times, no central authority in the United States decides which products stores carry. Retailers offer what customers want, which leads manufacturers to build what stores will stock. That cycle should guide any emerging economy.\n\nEconomics is the study of how people maximize the potential of life.\n\nMany desirable things come in limited supply. Petroleum, coconut milk, clean water, and even the perfect body are finite. Producing goods and trading them is what separates the rich from the poor, whether we are talking about individuals, companies, or countries.\n\nYou might wonder why Bill Gates owns a private jet while you do not. The simple answer is that he is rich and you are not. But why is he that rich?\n\nEconomics starts with one core assumption. People act to make themselves as wealthy as possible. They want to maximize their utility because they gain from it. That assumption holds true, and it explains the gap between you and Bill Gates.\n\nEconomists do not care what makes us happy. They simply note that each person has personal preferences and choices that shape their life. Bill Gates is wealthier because more people value his skills than they value yours. If tastes change and the world suddenly wants what you offer, you may one day afford a private jet too.\n\nWealth tends to come when what you love doing meets what you are good at.\n\nDeforestation is criticized in wealthy nations, but in poorer ones it is a basic way to survive. This shows that even though economics is universal, local realities split it along different lines.\n\nEconomists believe that working to improve our lives is good for any economy because it leads to creativity. What improves our lives depends on what we enjoy. Bill Gates's love of technology has improved the world.\n\nOsceola McCarthy lived alone in a small, barely furnished home with an old black-and-white TV that picked up only one channel. Her story was not about poverty. It was about her decision to give one hundred fifty thousand dollars to the University of Southern Mississippi, a school she had never attended, to set up a scholarship for needy students four years before her death. Her joy came from giving, not from spending on herself."
      },
      {
        title: 'When greed helps and when it hurts',
        text: "The black rhinoceros is one of the most endangered animals on earth. Their numbers fell from about sixty-five thousand in 1970 to around five thousand today. The cause is clear. On the black market, a single rhino horn can sell for up to thirty thousand dollars, which makes them targets for poachers looking for fast money.\n\nEconomists believe that if keeping rhinos alive were a private business, more of them would survive. A private owner would protect them because they are his income. Even if he sold some to trophy hunters, he would breed more to keep up with demand. Since rhinos belong to no one, nobody watches over them closely. Local villagers usually gain nothing from having rhinos nearby. The animals damage crops and can be dangerous around children.\n\nTo bring the community on board, authorities need a strong conservation plan that fits the interests of people who live near the rhinos. The plan has to give locals real reasons to protect the animals.\n\nPeople will do a lot for a worthy cause, but they will do more when they get paid for it.\n\nBad policy ignores incentives or forgets that people will change their actions when the rules change. A healthy economy rests on smart policies.\n\nThe trouble is that governments often do not know what good policies look like. As Gordon Gekko said in the movie Wall Street, greed is good, so make it work for you. Still, greed can also be harmful. Problems in economics appear when people pursuing self-interest end up hurting themselves or others.\n\nWe have to admit that greed and self-interest are part of human nature. People will act in their own interest, even when it hurts them in the long run.\n\nEconomics teaches us to design good incentives and to remember that people will always act in their own interest. The job is to steer that self-interest toward the common good."
      },
      {
        title: 'A modern game of thrones over economic power',
        text: "When monopolies form, the loser is usually the consumer. A monopoly kills innovation because no one is forcing the seller to do better. Without competition, prices climb and quality drops.\n\nGovernments try to fight monopolies with antitrust laws, but the rules vary by country. In some places, breaking up a giant company is routine. In others, regulators let monopolies grow in exchange for jobs or political support.\n\nThe real battle is over who controls the most valuable resources. In the twenty-first century, that means data. Whoever holds the most data can predict what people want before they know it themselves. That power lets a company set prices, shape opinions, and squeeze out smaller rivals.\n\nCountries are starting to treat data like oil, a resource that needs careful management. Some governments are pushing for rules that force big firms to share data or limit how they use it. Others want to keep the market open so homegrown companies can grow into giants.\n\nThe choices we make now will decide whether the next economy rewards a few giants or many smaller players. Either way, the fight over data is reshaping the global balance of power in ways we are only beginning to understand."
      },
      {
        title: 'How strong branding can fight racial bias',
        text: "Markets tend to reward the party with more information. What we do not know can hurt us. An ignorant company will not survive a competitive market. Economics teaches us how information is gathered, why we seek it, how we use it, and how we make decisions once we have it.\n\nIn the United States, the registry of convicted felons is open to the public. Employers can check an applicant's name against that list before offering a job. In theory, this should help anyone with a clean record. In practice, it often works against Black men. Statistics show that Black men make up a large share of ex-felons, so the stereotype that Black men are dangerous takes hold. Many employers assume the worst without even checking.\n\nStudies by economists have found something striking. Employers who do screen applicants for criminal records end up hiring more African American workers, especially men. The pattern is strongest among employers who hesitate to hire anyone with a record. Without better information, Black men will keep facing this hidden wall.\n\nThe need for information is why branding matters so much in trade.\n\nBranding matters most when product quality is hard to judge at a glance.\n\nBranding is what makes us buy a book without knowing its contents. It solves a consumer puzzle: how do you choose when you cannot judge quality until after you have paid?\n\nCustomers trust products based on the information a brand provides. Someone who buys Nike sneakers trusts that he is getting solid quality because of the Nike name.\n\nA healthy economy needs branding built on real information. Many countries survive on exports because they have built strong brands for what they sell.\n\nAccording to the World Bank, more than seven hundred million people still live on less than two dollars and fifteen cents a day."
      },
      {
        title: 'Human capital separates the novice from the expert',
        text: "Human capital is the total stock of skills a person carries. It covers education, intelligence, charm, creativity, work experience, entrepreneurial drive, and even skills that look basic from the outside. It is the one thing that stays with us when everything else is taken away.\n\nIn a market economy, the pay a skill commands depends less on how useful it is to society and more on how rare it is. People who reach the top of their field earn more because their service is scarce. Athletes like Stephen Curry earn far more than their peers because they have mastered their game at the highest level. Few players can match his style, which makes his talent rare.\n\nEconomics is like gravity. Ignore it and you will get hurt.\n\nHuman capital opens doors. It enriches us financially and personally, and it turns us into more rounded individuals who can work fewer hours for a better life. Through human capital, one job creates many more jobs around it.\n\nThe smartest investment you can make is in yourself.\n\nCurry's talent needs support. He hires a personal fitness coach, who then needs an assistant for other clients. He needs a private space to practice, which means hiring an architect and a builder.\n\nMost importantly, human capital separates the rich from the poor. Heavy investment in human capital pays back well over time.\n\nEvery person plays a role. An architect does not lay bricks, but the bricklayer's work cannot be ignored. Even if machines replace the bricklayer, those machines still need workers to assemble, run, and repair them. Without low-income workers, the architect or engineer could not get anything done."
      },
      {
        title: 'What slowly breaks an economy',
        text: "Economists argue that small groups often win in interest-group politics. Small, organized factions usually succeed in political fights because the cost of the favors they win gets spread across a much larger, less organized public. Small businesses, when given room to grow, can earn enough profit to pay strong taxes back to the government.\n\nIn countries where farmers make up a small slice of the population, like the United States, farmers receive large government subsidies. The picture flips in places like China and India, where farmers make up a huge share of the population. There, farmers must sell their crops below market price so that city dwellers can afford basic food. US farmers gain political favors while Chinese and Indian farmers bear the cost. In the end, the larger group subsidizes the smaller one.\n\nSmall businesses are the backbone of any healthy economy.\n\nNotice how little we care about rising costs until small businesses start to suffer?\n\nInflation is a related problem that deserves its own attention. Severe inflation wrecks an economy. It pushes people to spend their money quickly before it loses value. Workers scramble to use their pay before midday, worried that prices will spike by evening. Fixed-rate loans become rare because no lender wants repayment in money that may be worth less by the time it arrives.\n\nInflation can damage an economy. Even moderate inflation eats away at wealth if it is not controlled. Any money sitting as cash will lose value over time.\n\nMonetary policy is delicate. Done well, it supports growth and cushions shocks. Done badly, it causes real suffering."
      },
      {
        title: 'Exchange rates shape the global economy',
        text: "International economics should work like domestic economics, but it often does not. National borders are political lines, not economic ones. Trade between countries should still leave both sides better off. If it did not, it would waste time and resources.\n\nYou bought your car because you thought it was a quality vehicle at a fair price. The manufacturer sold it to make a profit. In the end, you and the seller each got something you valued.\n\nEven profitable international trade can be upset by exchange rates. The exchange rate decides how one country's money converts into another's. A Japanese yen is useful because it can buy goods and services. A dollar is useful for the same reason. In a perfect world, you could trade one dollar for a number of yen that would buy the same goods in Japan. If an item costs thirty dollars in the United States and the same item costs 750 cedis in Ghana, you would expect thirty dollars to be worth 750 cedis based on purchasing power. If the dollar version costs less than the cedi version, a smart trader can buy the item in dollars and sell it for a profit in cedis. Purchasing power works for goods, but it does not always cover services. A hairstylist cannot profit by styling hair for the value of a dollar in yen unless the flow runs the other way.\n\nThe better we do financially, the stronger our economies become.\n\nA global economy makes cooperation easier. Exchange rates do not have to match in value, but the trade has to help both sides. Many countries with weak exchange rates still do fine because the cost of living is low. A meal in Mumbai costs far less than a meal in Canada. Ten rupees can buy a better meal in Mumbai than ten dollars can buy in Canada. We may not be able to lock exchange rates in place, but we should encourage trade. Trade lets both sides walk away with a fair gain. Richer nations should be willing to buy from poorer ones."
      },
      {
        title: 'Using trade to fight poverty',
        text: "Imagine a machine that could turn a piece of cloth into a ten dollar bill, or a basket of avocados into two hundred yen. That machine would be priceless for developing countries. It would let them transform what they produce, like raw materials, cheap textiles, and basic goods, into things they could never make on their own, such as food, medicine, and technology. Countries with access to such a device could grow much faster than those without it, lifting millions out of poverty. We might think such a machine is impossible, but it exists. It is called trade.\n\nTrade is the only way we can swap clothes for money, food for technology, or a basket of fruit for cash. Trade brings many benefits.\n\nTrade builds wealth. It is one of the simplest ideas in economics, yet one of the most powerful. Trade opens the door to productivity, which is the engine of prosperity, and to specialization, which fuels productivity.\n\nTrade lowers costs for consumers, which boosts purchasing power. It creates a level playing field where both the buyer and the seller walk away satisfied.\n\nTrade helps developing countries too. It gives them access to markets in the developed world, opening doors that would otherwise stay closed.\n\nTrade creates wealth in developing nations. Export-focused industries often pay higher wages than other sectors.\n\nA strong economy lifts every citizen, not just a chosen few.\n\nA major cause of global poverty is the failure of wealthy nations to reshape the world economy. The only way to balance the system is for developed countries to support developing ones. Cooperation beats self-interest in this fight."
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thoughts on a working economy',
        text: "The difference between a developing nation, an underdeveloped nation, and a developed nation comes down to the economy. A country's economy decides its place in the world and its bargaining power. Most developed nations understand the details of economics. They know how to trade, where to trade, and when to trade. Not every nation can reach developed status, but we can close the gap between rich and poor by learning the economics of trade.\n\nWe must understand the role of both government and the private sector in keeping the economy healthy. We have to watch out for the dangers of monopoly and the damage of runaway inflation. Letting the government run the entire economy can lead to ruin. The best way to a strong economy is partnership between government and the private sector.\n\nIf we unite as nations to fight poverty, we can close the gap between rich and poor through trade.\n\nTry this\n\nIf you have a business idea, study current trends and real needs. How could it make your customers' lives easier or better? Do not chase huge profits at the cost of quality. Some of the world's best brands became great because of the quality they delivered. Build your brand name through social media and other tools you can reach.\n\nRead it till the end?"
      }
    ]
  },

  'neurotribes-the-legacy-of-autism-and-the-future-of-neurodiversity.json': {
    base: { id: 'neurotribes-the-legacy-of-autism-and-the-future-of-neurodiversity', title: 'Neurotribes', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781680553047 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Inside the garden of neurodiversity',
        text: "Picture a garden with a tall oak, delicate roses, soft grass, and gentle water lilies, each one special in its own way. No one would blame a daisy for not standing as tall as an apple tree, or scold an apple tree for not smelling as sweet as mint. People are different too, but society still struggles to accept the idea of neurodiversity.\n\nThe world moves forward because of differences, not because everyone matches.\n\nNeurodiversity is the idea that human brains work in different ways. Each brain thinks, socializes, and handles mental tasks in its own pattern. The concept covers people with autism spectrum disorder, ADHD, dyslexia, and similar conditions.\n\nYou have a rare chance to learn about neurodiversity now, because good information has been hard to find. Views of the autism spectrum have swung wildly through history. Some people with autism were treated as geniuses. Others were subjected to harsh procedures or even killed.\n\nThe future depends on the present, and the present depends on you. Do you want to know more? Do you think you or someone you love might be on this spectrum? Step into our garden and see what you find."
      },
      {
        title: 'Between admiration and blame',
        text: "Autism existed long before anyone named it. Thomas Jefferson, Charles Darwin, Mozart, and Einstein may all have been on the autistic spectrum. Their unusual way of seeing the world led to breakthroughs in science and art, but they often suffered from being misunderstood and could not fit into the usual norms.\n\nTheir contemporary, Henry Cavendish, was an eighteenth-century scientist often called a wizard. His story captures the typical struggles and triumphs of people with autism.\n\nFrom an early age, he was observant but odd to most people his age. He had no interest in social events, women, or entertainment, and spent his days experimenting in his laboratory. He worked out formulas that were centuries ahead of world science, including laws later attributed to Ohm, Dalton, and Charles, well before those scientists were born. He never took notes, so he got no credit.\n\nCavendish cared about pure science, not society's applause. He never patented his work but kept making new discoveries. Using a pendulum and months of careful work, he measured the density of the earth with remarkable accuracy and laid the foundation for modern physics without realizing it.\n\nDespite his genius, Cavendish struggled with communication. He found crowds exhausting and could not build a personal life. His peers described him as brilliant but cold and even arrogant, ignoring them on purpose. In truth, social contact drained him far more than science, but few people understood him then.\n\nWhat matters is the quality of social contact, not the quantity.\n\nDespite the judgment he faced, Cavendish was wealthy, which let him do as he pleased. Most people with autism, both in his time and today, do not have that luxury. Not all of them are brilliant in physics or art, but all deserve a happy life. They do not always realize it themselves. From Cavendish's time to ours, the view of autism has changed many times, and not always for the better."
      },
      {
        title: 'History moves on, but autism stays',
        text: "Autism spectrum symptoms range from a deep passion for a narrow subject to severe discomfort with ordinary touch. The harder parts of the condition usually outweigh the gifts. Today, medicine is trying to build inclusive spaces where people with autism can feel safe and adapt to society, but it has not always been this way.\n\nIn the 1800s, people like Cavendish were seen as odd or problematic. In the 1900s, they caught the attention of scientists, including Hans Asperger.\n\nDeeply curious about medicine and psychology, Asperger was especially drawn to children with unusual behavior who could not fit into regular schools. Unlike the views of his time, he did not see these children as broken or underdeveloped. He treated them as colleagues helping him unlock one of the great mysteries of psychiatry.\n\nRespect motivates people to cooperate far more than force ever will.\n\nIn this unusual partnership, Asperger developed a diagnostic system that worked better than forcing children through tests. He believed the clearest signs of autism showed up in everyday life. Based on his work, modern doctors list these signs in children around age three: little interest in play or in games without a story, no response to their own name, no speech or speech made up of invented phrases, obsession with small details, and talking about themselves in the second or third person.\n\nAsperger believed such children did not need criticism. They needed timely help adapting to society, which could make up for their struggles. Not everyone shared his view. In the early 1900s, eugenics became popular. It argued that only people close to an ideal had the right to reproduce in order to improve the human race. Eugenics had strong support in the United States and became a key part of Nazi ideology in Germany. Thousands of patients in psychiatric hospitals, including people with even mild signs of autism, were sterilized or killed.\n\nAfter the horrors of Nazism, the world reconsidered its view of autism and gave Asperger's research the credit it deserved. Modern medicine now focuses on kinder, more supportive care."
      },
      {
        title: 'Autism is not your enemy',
        text: "Medicine used to treat autism as simple bad behavior, especially vivid in children. Parents were told to raise them better, be stricter or warmer, and some doctors even blamed family tension for the condition.\n\nA mother and father already stressed by their child's struggles were then made to feel guilty as well. Sadly, this view often won out over the truth that autism is something you are born with, because it offered a vague hope of a cure.\n\nSteve Silberman and Oliver Sacks have written that there is much work to be done.\n\nIf you or someone you love has autism, the first thing to accept is simple: it is nobody's fault. Autism is present from birth, although it may not show clear signs until a child is around five. Vaccines and other medical treatments do not cause autism, despite common fears, even though the timing of those treatments can overlap with when symptoms first appear.\n\nWe cannot always control the ocean of life. We can only learn to ride its waves.\n\nPeople cannot prevent autism through any known means, but we can help children adapt. In early childhood, the brain grows fast and soaks up huge amounts of information. Every day spent working with a child on the spectrum is precious. Several methods help people with autism.\n\nPsychotherapy helps children work through fears and build emotional bonds.\n\nSpecial education finds the most comfortable and effective way for each child to learn.\n\nMedication cannot cure autism, but it can improve quality of life and ease related issues like aggression.\n\nDiet cannot transform the picture either, but good nutrition supports a healthy body, since many autistic children are very picky eaters.\n\nTrust a specialist to choose the right treatment. Doctors usually order a long list of tests before treatment because every brain is different, as is every path to happiness. Autism is not a life sentence or an enemy. It is a neighbor we can learn to live with so we can all live our best lives."
      },
      {
        title: 'Opening Pandora’s box',
        text: "Autism was often confused with other mental conditions because research was thin. Some symptoms looked similar, but patients could not get better because doctors kept misdiagnosing them. In the 1990s, the media began to panic about a sudden autism epidemic sweeping the world. In fact, it was not a cruel twist of fate but a sign of better research.\n\nRecognizing autism was like opening Pandora's box. Scientists became more aware of it, and the idea kept expanding. What had once seemed like a single condition turned out to be a whole spectrum with no single pattern, varying from person to person.\n\nBetween 1990 and 2000, the number of children diagnosed with autism grew by twenty-two percent each year. On one hand, that was scary and fed dystopian fears. On the other, it gave hope to many parents.\n\nThe path to happiness runs through painful truths about ourselves.\n\nAlong with the hard realization that autism touches many more people than once thought, society started to build a more comfortable world. Inclusive schools, clubs, and surveys appeared, helping us understand each person's needs better.\n\nModern medicine offers many ways to spot autism. A full diagnosis needs a doctor's evaluation and detailed testing, but some tests are available online. The Autism Quotient helps adults see which common autism traits they carry. The Ritvo Autism and Asperger Diagnostic Scale is often used in research to detect autism in adults. The Empathy Quotient measures empathy levels, which often correlate with autism.\n\nIn the myth of Pandora, hope sat at the bottom of the box and never faded. So if you notice signs of autism in yourself or have already been diagnosed, do not despair. Recognizing your own traits does not make you weak. It helps you find tools to adapt and shows that you care about yourself. That deserves respect."
      },
      {
        title: 'When the garden comes into bloom',
        text: "Different plants need different care. A water lily cannot grow in sand. A cactus will rot in soggy soil. People need different conditions to reach their full potential too. For those on the autism spectrum, this matters even more, because the world often piles pressure on them.\n\nThe setting around a person with autism can be too loud and chaotic. Some researchers see this as a strange inheritance from a long-ago time, when human life looked nothing like today. Modern life lacks clear patterns, fills the air with sharp sounds, and piles on new situations without warning, all of which feed stress. By contrast, structured spaces such as a calm classroom or a steady home can lower that stress and help them do their best work.\n\nHands-on learning helps many autistic people thrive.\n\nThese special needs do not mean people with autism cannot shine in a busy world. Temple Grandin, known for her deep work in animal science and welfare, sits on the spectrum. So does Satoshi Tajiri, the creator of Pokémon, and Sir Anthony Hopkins, who has won an Oscar for his acting. All of them found work that played to their strengths and softened their weaknesses, and they rose to the top. Their fierce passion helped them outshine many so-called neurotypical experts.\n\nYour quirks can be your greatest power, because no one else has them.\n\nAnother way to picture autism is to think of operating systems. If your laptop runs on Mac instead of Windows, it does not mean it is broken. It just supports a different system and handles tasks in its own way. The internet ties together Mac, Windows, Android, Linux, and iOS, and it grew to its current size because all those platforms worked together.\n\nSociety needs different kinds of thinkers, each with their own corner to do work that only they can do. Nature thrives where many kinds of plants grow together. The modern world has to welcome neurodiversity if it wants to grow well.\n\nApril second was set by the United Nations in 2007 as a global day to mark autism awareness and protect the rights of those on the spectrum."
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thoughts on a more inclusive world',
        text: "Autism is common, and it has been with us for a very long time. Its features include a pull inward, struggles with socializing or learning, and a one-of-a-kind way of thinking.\n\nAutism is not one condition but a spectrum, so signs vary from person to person.\n\nWith welcoming spaces and steady routines, people on the spectrum can and often do reach high levels of achievement. A society that embraces neurodiversity benefits everyone, not just those on the spectrum.\n\nTry this\n\nTake an online autism questionnaire for grown-ups, such as the ADI-R. It can help you decide whether to book an appointment with a professional for a fuller evaluation. Pick a favorite fidget tool for stimming, which means small repeated motions that often soothe and ease tension. Even if you do not live with autism, it can help you unwind. On April second, wear blue to show your support for autism awareness. It is a simple way to build shared understanding in our communities.\n\nRead it till the end?"
      }
    ]
  },

  'never-binge-again.json': {
    base: { id: 'never-binge-again', title: 'Never Binge Again', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781680648928 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Without a strict healthy eating habit, food addiction can take hold quickly',
        text: "Many adults struggle with food addiction and, as a result, become obese. This is unfortunate and unhealthy for anyone. Obesity comes from overeating and a sedentary life. Once you lose control of your eating, the next stop on the track is addiction.\n\nCultivating healthy eating habits is important to avoid illness and other complications.\n\nMost people think losing weight should be easy. They were not always obese, so surely they can get back there. The sad truth is that climbing out of food addiction is hard. Like any addiction, food addiction pushes you to keep eating long after you are full, trying to fill a craving. Even if you just ate, you eat again until you cannot move.\n\nAddiction is dangerous. Discipline is what protects us from overindulging in our worst habits.\n\nHere is where things get tricky. Your mind starts playing games with you. It insists there is no way out and tells you to accept your fate. You must not give in. Your health matters more than the comfort of old habits, and you have to take it back. The market is full of quick fixes and self-help guides that promise to cure food addiction and obesity. Most of them do not help. They only frustrate and discourage people who are desperate for change, pushing them into another downward spiral. This summary is different. The principles and tactics here come from real experiments tested on thousands of people.\n\nQuick-fix solutions are almost always false. Look for advice from trained professionals.\n\nIn the chapters ahead, we will cover everyday harmful eating habits, how to fight them, and how to return to peak fitness. Do not commit to any quick fix. They are usually designed to take your money. Glenn Livingstone, PhD, is no ordinary hack. He is a trained professional whose methods are backed by extensive research.\n\nRecovery begins with honesty about the trap you are in.\n\nThe story usually starts the same way. A bad day at work, a fight with a friend, or a slow wave of boredom, and suddenly the fridge feels like the only place that makes sense. The binge feels good for a few minutes. Then the guilt arrives, and you promise yourself tomorrow will be different. Tomorrow comes, and the same pull returns. That cycle is the trap, and breaking it takes more than willpower. It takes a clear plan and a way to talk back to the voice in your head.\n\nWhat follows in this book is that plan."
      },
      {
        title: 'Building a food plan that stops the binge cycle',
        text: "Bingeing on food is one of the toughest addictions to break. Unlike drugs or alcohol, you cannot just stop eating. You have to decide what to eat, where to eat, and how to eat. That decision drags people onto a ride very few can step off. Many find diets and food plans hard to follow. The standard formulas available today are too rigid to fit the many different faces of bingeing.\n\nFood addiction comes from an inability to control how much we eat.\n\nOne reason we cannot stick to a diet is the inner pig. The pig stands for the part of you that thinks only about food. It hijacks your survival drive and pushes you toward eating habits that do NOT serve your best interests. It is an out-of-control eating machine that will ruin everything if you let it. It sabotages your plans and exists only to feed itself.\n\nYou have power over your mind, not over outside events. Realize that, and you will find strength, as Marcus Aurelius once wrote.\n\nThe pig is not you, and you have everything it takes to control it. You can cage it and follow the food plan that works for you. For this to succeed, you have to take one hundred percent responsibility for setting up your plan. It is fine to ask a nutritionist for advice, but you have to choose what works.\n\nYour food plan should be crystal clear. Write it down and pin it to a wall so you can see when you are slipping. As you start, listen for the squeals of the pig, the voice that tries to block your progress. To quiet it, set up rules that guide you through the process. First, define the eating habits, or habits in general, that you will never indulge in again. For example, pick a food or food group to drop for good. Second, define the habits you will always follow, like eating more vegetables, drinking more water, or working out. Third, choose eating habits that your plan does not restrict, and label those foods as unrestricted. Fourth, place some foods under conditional, and define the exceptions that allow them. For example, you might decide to drink soda only after finishing a workout."
      },
      {
        title: 'Discomfort is normal as you follow your new food plan',
        text: "Some discomfort is normal as you walk this road. You are at war with the pig inside you, and it will remind you of every pleasure you got from junk food. It will tell you that giving up a food group is slowly killing you. It will say that you are suffering and that you are suffering a lot.\n\nIn truth, discomfort is a normal response and should not be treated as a reason to quit.\n\nYou will feel like part of you is slipping away. You will face your cravings head on. And in a society that celebrates unhealthy eating, you will feel overwhelmed by your own choices. You might agree that there is no rest for those who decide to eat right.\n\nStill, there is a way to win no matter how much pressure builds against you. You should never forget your food plan and your Nevers, Always, Unrestricteds, and Conditionals. Remember that every voice telling you to give up is the pig. Keep reminding yourself of the promise you made never to binge again or never to indulge in unhealthy food.\n\nIf you slip and binge, you have to know how to get back on track, or you will give up entirely. To stay ahead of your fears, guilt, regrets, and failures, you must rely on progress rather than perfection. There are many reasons not to chase perfection. One of them is that the pig can use your perfectionism against you when you fall. It will tell you that you are weak and broken, that you cannot do right by yourself, that you cannot keep your word. So you must build a framework that defends your confidence and your will to keep going.\n\nTo pull yourself back up, identify what caused the binge. Then review your food plan and figure out which of your Conditionals is the root cause. Move that Conditional into the Never category. Most importantly, understand that one slip should not stain your commitment to the Never Binge Again practice."
      },
      {
        title: 'Knowing when to change your food plan and when to leave it alone',
        text: "Change is part of life, and your food plan will need to change too. New research might reveal flaws in your current plan. Stay open to those changes. Just do not let your instinct to improve become an excuse to feed the pig.\n\nIdentify your main reason for change, the new rules you want to introduce, and why the change matters.\n\nGlenn Livingstone, PhD, has said he does not believe in the numbering system some addicts use to mark their progress. For example, some people count the days since they last gave in. That approach keeps them stuck in a battle against their impulses, reminding them that they cannot live a normal life.\n\nInstead, Livingstone advises stripping the pig of any recognition or power that would let it pop back up when you make mistakes. Alongside that, learn what deprivation is doing for you. What is your abstinence from unhealthy eating giving you? That question will help you stay committed to your plan.\n\nIt is hard to stick to a plan when the food industry keeps trying to sell you unhealthy products dressed up as healthy ones. Look past the fancy packaging and see the truth underneath.\n\nDo not wait for other people's approval before doing what you know you should.\n\nTake full ownership of your food plan. Do not look for validation from anyone else. You can also keep this Never Binge Again philosophy to yourself. Many people in similar situations are still trapped in the belief that they need help, so they may push back against you because your success reminds them that breaking free is possible."
      },
      {
        title: 'You have the power to choose what you eat',
        text: "Many people believe that addiction is a disease in itself, and that those who suffer from it can never fully fight it off. That false idea convinces victims that they are powerless and that the best they can do is spend their whole lives nursing this mystery disease.\n\nPeople get brainwashed into thinking relapses are normal, that full recovery is impossible. That belief cripples the minds of those battling food addiction. They feel powerless and find something to blame when they slip. A mindset built on responsibility does the opposite.\n\nWhen you take responsibility for where you are and believe you have the power to do better, change becomes easier.\n\nNever let your cravings decide who you are. Take control of them instead.\n\nAlong the way, watch out for the common mistakes that send people back to square one. You might be tempted to take a short break from your diet because you are seeing some early progress. You might decide to indulge in a Never food because you can burn it off in your next workout. It is also common for people to slip into an unhealthy lifestyle while telling themselves they are practicing self-love.\n\nNo matter how you might stumble, you have to stay focused on the task. Stay true to the commitment and the promise you made to eat right. Remember that the cost of failure is far heavier than the temporary pleasure of junk food. With that in mind, lean on discipline. It is the only path to real freedom.\n\nLong ago, the ancient people of South America used chocolate as a form of currency."
      },
      {
        title: 'Beware of guilt and shame as you fight the urge to binge',
        text: "Guilt and shame act as flags that remind us we have done something wrong. They show up when you start the Never Binge Again program. When you slip, they remind you of the mistake and tell you that you have gone off course.\n\nEmotions are useful signals, but holding on to them too long is dangerous.\n\nDo not feed on guilt and shame by beating yourself up until you start doubting your ability to stay the course. Instead, acknowledge the guilt and shame, learn from the mistake, and plan a fix that will help you stay immune to that temptation in the future. In hindsight, past failures make you stronger, especially when you learn to channel the energy they release.\n\nAnyone who has never made a mistake has never tried anything new, as Albert Einstein once said.\n\nStay alert mentally. It is common for people to blame unconscious bingeing for their relapses. That idea is false. We tend to ignore what we are doing when it goes against the principles we want to live by. Dr. Livingstone suggests keeping a journal and writing down every way the pig tried to make you fail.\n\nThis habit helps you spot those traps in the future and trains your body to become resistant to them. Still, even after you have done all the right things, what happens if you are still struggling?\n\nAt that point, you have to rely on your free will to choose healthy food again and again until it sticks. Free will is the force that pushes us to choose our own path. It reminds us that every choice has consequences. So when you reach a crossroads, hold on to your right to choose health, and use it until your addiction fades."
      },
      {
        title: 'Final thoughts on a healthier life',
        text: "More people than we like to admit struggle with food addiction. That addiction leads to serious health problems and, in some cases, death. Food addiction does not appear overnight. It usually grows out of the difficulty of managing how much we eat.\n\nFighting food addiction takes real willpower and support from people who love you. Once you start on the path to freedom from binging, it is important to take slow, careful steps so your body does not snap back into old habits. A healthy support system is a powerful tool for learning and keeping a new habit.\n\nNo matter how ready you think you are, expect outside forces to test your commitment. Your success depends on your ability to tame your mind, learn from mistakes, and keep improving. The goal is to eat better and live healthier. That goal has to be etched into your mind so it becomes the engine that keeps you going when you feel like quitting.\n\nFocus on making progress, however small. There is no rush, as long as you stay committed and steady. If you feel like giving up, consider taking a short break, just long enough to rest but not long enough to slip back into old habits.\n\nTry this\n\nBuild a food plan that will give you the body you want. As you build it, remove junk food permanently from your diet and add meals that are both nutritious and low in carbs. Introduce your body to this new way of living in slow, careful steps at a pace that feels comfortable.\n\nRead it till the end?"
      }
    ]
  }
};
